# CODEOWNERS — {{PROJECT_NAME}}
#
# This file maps repository paths to the roles responsible for reviewing them,
# so that review responsibility is legible and every part of the project has an
# owner. GitHub requests a review from the listed owners when a pull request
# touches a matching path. The handles below are placeholders of the form
# @org/role-team — replace them with the people or teams named in ROLES.md.
# Later entries win, so order from general to specific.

# Default owner: the project manager catches anything not matched below.
*                       @org/project-manager

# Data lives with the data engineer: source data, schema, identifiers, quality.
/data/                  @org/data-engineer
/DATA-DICTIONARY.md     @org/subject-matter-expert

# Pipelines and reusable code are the developer's and engineer's shared ground:
# the engineer owns the data flow, the developer owns the tooling around it.
/pipelines/             @org/data-engineer @org/developer-team
/src/                   @org/developer-team

# Documentation carries meaning, so the subject-matter expert reviews it.
# (The data dictionary above is the one exception they own outright.)
/docs/                  @org/subject-matter-expert

# Governance and the charter set the project's terms: the project manager owns
# them, with legal as a second reviewer on the terms that bind partners.
/GOVERNANCE.md          @org/project-manager @org/legal
/CHARTER.md             @org/project-manager
/ROLES.md               @org/project-manager

# Environment and CI affect reproducibility for everyone — the developer owns
# them so the pinned environment and pipeline stay in sync.
/environment.yml        @org/developer-team
/.github/               @org/developer-team
